## Agent Registration & Session Restart

### The Problem
OpenCode caches available agents when a session begins. New markdown files added to .opencode/agent/ mid-session are not dynamically recognized by the Task tool (which triggers an "Unknown agent type" error).

### The Solution: Required Restart
If you create a new agent via a skill, you **must** instruct the user to restart the current OpenCode session before attempting to use the new agent via the Task tool.

### CLI Testing (Pre-Restart Verification)
Before asking the user to restart, test the newly created agent via the OpenCode CLI to verify the frontmatter parses correctly:
`ash
opencode run --agent <agent-name> "test"
`
*(Note: If the agent is a subagent, the CLI will throw a warning about falling back to the default agent. This is expected and proves the YAML frontmatter is structurally sound.)*

## Subagent Spawning Prevention

### The Problem

OpenCode's `task` permission defaults to `"allow"`. This means ANY agent (including subagents) can use the `task()` tool to spawn other subagents, creating nested chains:

```
User → @critic-cio (subagent 1) → spawns subagent 2 → spawns subagent 3
```

This causes:
- **Cost inflation** - Each nested subagent consumes tokens
- **Latency** - Nested execution takes longer
- **Confusion** - Hard to trace which agent did what
- **Broken UX** - Questions from deeply nested agents may not appear in TUI (GitHub #7654)

### The Solution: Hard Deny

For **review-only subagents**, ALWAYS include:

```yaml
permission:
  task:
    "*": deny
```

**Do NOT rely solely on prompt guardrails.** LLMs may ignore "do not" instructions.

### Complete Template for Review-Only Subagents

```yaml
---
description: [What this agent reviews/validates]
mode: subagent
permission:
  edit: deny        # Read-only (blocks write/edit/apply_patch)
  bash: allow       # Required so the agent can read files (Bun fallback)
  task:
    "*": deny              # CRITICAL: Prevents nested subagent spawning
  skill:
    perplexity-search: allow
    notebooklm: allow
    content-trend-researcher: allow
---

[Agent prompt with guardrail text:]

Guardrail (anti-recursion): You are a single reviewer pass. Do NOT spawn or delegate to other agents. The task tool is DISABLED for this agent.
```

### Agents That SHOULD Have Task Access

These are **orchestrator agents** that intentionally delegate:

| Agent            | Mode    | Why Task Allowed         |
| ----------------| ------- | ------------------------ |
| content-factory | primary | Orchestrates writers, researchers |
| youtube-shorts  | primary | Orchestrates writer, critic, designer |
| content-repurposer | primary | Orchestrates repurposing workflow |
| image-creator   | primary | Orchestrates image generation |

### Agents That Should NOT Have Task Access

These are **review-only subagents** that should work independently:

| Agent                | Mode     | Why Task Denied         |
| --------------------| -------- | ----------------------- |
| critic-cio           | subagent | Single-pass reviewer    |
| cio-review           | subagent | Single-pass reviewer    |
| peer-review          | subagent | Independent validation  |
| seo-auditor          | subagent | Standalone analysis     |
| brand-voice-validator| subagent | Single-purpose check    |
| gen-headlines        | subagent | Independent generation  |
| offer-architect      | subagent | Single-purpose creation |

### Detection: How to Spot the Problem

In logs, look for:
```
service=session ... created ... parentID=...
```

Multiple sessions with `parentID` relationships indicate nested spawning.

### Related Issues

- GitHub #7654: Questions from nested sub-agents don't appear in TUI
- GitHub #14308: Custom agents cannot access task tool despite configuration

